{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17582462","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17582462"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:41+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T06:43:41+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"182"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/182"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.33,0.13,0.07,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78770"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/182"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"182"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64119"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"108"},{"type":"tags","id":"4927"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"10851"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"71"},{"type":"contributions","id":"654"},{"type":"contributions","id":"733"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27047"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45712"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78770","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/78770"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 33-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-week history of productive cough with blood-streaked sputum, fevers, night sweats, and pleuritic chest pain. He reports three kilograms of unintentional weight loss. He recently returned from a three-month trip to India. He has no significant medical history and takes no regular medications. He is a non-smoker and works as an accountant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears unwell. His pulse rate is 95/min, blood pressure 125/75 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 97% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Chest examination reveals bronchial breathing in the right upper zone. A chest X-ray shows right upper lobe infiltrates with cavitation.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Sputum microscopy and culture","Interferon-gamma release assay","Tuberculin skin test","High-resolution CT chest","Bronchoscopy with bronchoalveolar lavage"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of pulmonary tuberculosis including haemoptysis, constitutional symptoms, and upper lobe infiltrates with cavitation on chest X-ray. The recent travel to a high-prevalence country increases the pre-test probability.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESputum microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E is the most important initial investigation for diagnosing pulmonary tuberculosis. Three early morning samples should be collected on consecutive days as they have the highest yield. Microscopy can provide rapid preliminary results within hours, while culture confirms the diagnosis and provides drug susceptibility information, typically taking 2-6 weeks.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInterferon-gamma release assay\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate as it cannot distinguish between latent and active tuberculosis infection. It measures T-cell response to \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E antigens and is primarily used for screening in high-risk populations.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETuberculin skin test\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as it cannot distinguish between active disease, prior infection, and BCG vaccination. Like interferon-gamma release assay, it is used for screening rather than diagnosis of active disease.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh-resolution CT chest\u003C/strong\u003E may show characteristic findings such as tree-in-bud opacities, cavitation, and upper lobe consolidation but cannot confirm the diagnosis without microbiological evidence. While imaging can support the diagnosis, it should not delay collection of appropriate specimens.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBronchoscopy with bronchoalveolar lavage\u003C/strong\u003E is an invasive procedure that should be reserved for cases where sputum samples are non-diagnostic or cannot be obtained. It would not be appropriate as an initial investigation when the patient can produce sputum.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Sputum microscopy and culture is important for the diagnosis of pulmonary tuberculosis","Three consecutive early morning sputum samples should be collected to optimise diagnostic yield","Bronchoscopy is reserved for cases where sputum samples are non-diagnostic"],"references":["Cudahy P, Shenoi SV. Diagnostics for pulmonary tuberculosis. Postgrad Med J. 2016;92:187-193.","Koenig SP, Furin J.Update in Tuberculosis/Pulmonary Infections 2015. Am J Respir Crit Care Med. 2016;194(2):142-146","Davidson S, Walker BR, Colledge NR, Ralston S, Penman ID. Davidson\u2019s principles and practice of medicine. 22 ed. Edinburgh: Churchill Livingstone/Elsevier; 2014. p688-96.","Mase S, Ramsay A, Ng N, Henry M, Hopewell PC, Cunningham J, Urbanczik R, Perkins M, Aziz MA, Pai M. Yield of serial sputum specimen examinations in the diagnosis of pulmonary tuberculosis: a systematic review. Int J Tuberc Lung Dis 2007;11(5):485-95."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64119"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"182"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64119"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-12T16:53:16+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-12T16:54:05+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"182"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"78770"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Investigations","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"head